<h2 id="articletitle" class="regserif entry-title">
It&rsquo;s diabetes, y&rsquo;all: Paula Deen reportedly has type 2
</h2>
<div id="articlemeta">
<h4 class="heavyseriflbl sm byline author vcard">
zosia bielski
</h4>
<h5 class="sans sm updated">
<span class="articlecreditline">Globe and Mail Blog</span>
</h5>
<h5 class="articledateline sans sm">Posted on <time pubdate datetime="2012-01-13 18:15 -0500">Friday, January 13, 2012 6:15PM EST</time></h5>
</div>
<aside class="articleseealso articleseealsoheader">
<ul>
</ul>
</aside>
<!-- /seealsotop -->
<div class="articlecommentcountholder heavyserif">
<a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/the-hot-button/its-diabetes-yall-paula-deen-reportedly-has-type-2/article2302295/comments/" class="articlecommentcount" title="Go to the comments page">43 comments</a>
<span class="goindicator"></span>
</div>
<ul class="articletoolbar s6of12 sans tiny">
<li class="articleemail">
<a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/the-hot-button/its-diabetes-yall-paula-deen-reportedly-has-type-2/article2302295/email/" class="replacedicon" rel="email" title="Email this to a friend">Email</a>
</li>
<li class="articletwitter">
<a href="http://twitter.com/share?url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/the-hot-button/its-diabetes-yall-paula-deen-reportedly-has-type-2/article2302295/&text=It&rsquo;s diabetes, y&rsquo;all: Paula Deen reportedly has type 2&via=globeandmail" data-url="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/the-hot-button/its-diabetes-yall-paula-deen-reportedly-has-type-2/article2302295/" data-counturl="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/the-hot-button/its-diabetes-yall-paula-deen-reportedly-has-type-2/article2302295/" data-count="true" data-text="It&rsquo;s diabetes, y&rsquo;all: Paula Deen reportedly has type 2" data-via="globeandmail" class="twitter-share-button">Tweet</a>
</li>
<li class="articlefacebook">
<fb:like href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/the-hot-button/its-diabetes-yall-paula-deen-reportedly-has-type-2/article2302295/?utm_source=facebook.com&utm_medium=Referrer%3A+Social+Network+%2F+Media&utm_content=2302295&utm_campaign=Shared+Web+Article+Links" show_faces="false" action="recommend" font="verdana" layout="button_count" width="90"></fb:like>
</li>
<li class="articleprint">
<span class="replacedicon"></span>
<span class="printoptions"><a href="http://license.icopyright.net/g2/3.8425?icx_id=%2ficopyright%2f%3fartid%3d2302295" title="Print this page" target="_blank">Print</a>/<a href="http://license.icopyright.net/3.8425?icx_id=%2ficopyright%2f%3fartid%3d2302295" target="_blank" title="License this story">License</a></span>
</li>
<li class="articletextsize">
<a href="#" class="txttool txtsmaller">Decrease text size</a>
<a href="#" class="txttool txtlarger">Increase text size</a>
</li>
</ul>
</header>
<div id="minisky" class="ad s2of12">
<script type="text/javascript">aPs="t1"; var t1AC=fnTkt('a'+'ai',120,240,ai,'j',nc); document.write(t1AC); </script>
</div>
<div class="articlecopy s6of12 fl entry-content">
<p>
News that Paula Deen, the queen of greasy, sugar-loaded Southern cooking, may have type 2 diabetes was <a href="http://www.buzzfeed.com/gavon/top-25-reasons-paul-deen-has-diabetes" target="_blank">met with disdain across the Web on Friday</a>.
</p>
<p>
After all, the Food Network star was the brains behind creations like the &ldquo;<a href="http://boingboing.net/2012/01/13/paula-deen-celebrity-chef-cri.html" target="_blank">Lady&rsquo;s Brunch Burger</a>,&rdquo; which famously served up a fried egg, bacon and burger between two glazed doughnuts. Let&rsquo;s not forget the equally inexplicable <a href="http://www.pauladeen.com/recipes/recipe_view/bill_nicholsons_krispy_kreme_bread_pudding/" target="_blank">Krispy Kreme bread pudding</a>, <a href="http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/paula-deen/deep-fried-lasagna-recipe/index.html" target="_blank">deep fried lasagna</a> and <a href="http://www.pauladeen.com/recipes/recipe_view/deep_fried_stuffing_on_a_stick/" target="_blank">deep fried stuffing on a stick</a>.
</p><span class="hdivider"></span>
<aside class="articleseealso entry-content-asset">
<header><h4 class="regseriflbl large">More related to this story</h4></header>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/the-hot-button/fast-food-breakfast-think-twice-about-having-that-coffee/article1969203/" name="&lpos=Inline Article Related Links&lid=top - 1">Fast food breakfast? Think twice about having that coffee </a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/health/new-health/health-nutrition/leslie-beck/cut-sugar-to-lower-triglycerides/article1999190/" name="&lpos=Inline Article Related Links&lid=top - 2">Cut sugar to lower triglycerides </a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/health/new-health/conditions/diabetes/statin-use-linked-to-higher-diabetes-rates-in-women/article2297735/" name="&lpos=Inline Article Related Links&lid=top - 3">Statin use linked to higher diabetes rates in women</a></li>
</ul>
</aside>
<span class="hdivider revhdivider"></span>
<!-- /seealsotop -->
<p>
But reactions turned even more derisive when it was <a href="http://www.thedaily.com/page/2012/01/13/011312-gossip-paula-deen-1-2/" target="_blank">reported</a> that the Georgia-born chef had landed <a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/cheats/2012/01/13/paula-deen-has-diabetes-report.html" target="_blank">a multimillion-dollar deal</a> to hawk a diabetes drug for a pharmaceutical company.
</p>
<p>
It remains to be seen whether Ms. Deen will try her hand at healthier recipes, or continue pushing deep-fried confections on America while on this purportedly lucrative pharma contract.
</p>
<p>
With the news, eyes are also now turning back on Anthony Bourdain, who seethed that Ms. Deen is &ldquo;the worst, most dangerous person to America&rdquo; <a href="http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2011/08/paula-deen-anthony-bourdain-food-network-fight.html" target="_blank">back in August</a>.
</p>
<p>
&ldquo;She revels in unholy connections with evil corporations and she&rsquo;s proud of the fact that her food is ... bad for you,&rdquo; the No Reservations host told TV Guide. &ldquo;I would think twice before telling an already obese nation that it is OK to eat food that is killing us.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
Then, Ms. Deen pulled the class card, <a href="http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/paula_tells_tony_get_life_jswHsIgTk3teIhd7cXJTFI" target="_blank">retorting</a>:
</p>
<p>
&ldquo;You know, not everybody can afford to pay $58 for prime rib or $650 for a bottle of wine. My friends and I cook for regular families who worry about feeding their kids and paying the bills ... It wasn&rsquo;t that long ago that I was struggling to feed my family, too.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
(Feeding them luscious <a href="http://www.pauladeen.com/recipes/recipe_view/twinkie_pie/" target="_blank">Twinkie Pie</a>? Here&rsquo;s hoping not.)
</p>
<p>
New York Times columnist Frank Bruni <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/25/opinion/bruni-unsavory-culinary-elitism.html?_r=3&ref=dining" target="_blank">jumped into the fray</a> then too, dissing Mr. Bourdain for being an elitist culinary hypocrite who was serving up fatty duck confit as he assailed Ms. Deen&rsquo;s monstrosities. </p>
<p>
&ldquo;You can almost imagine Bourdain and Deen as political candidates, a blue-state paternalist squaring off against a red-state populist over correct living versus liberty in all its artery-clogging, self-destructive glory,&rdquo; Mr. Bruni wrote.
</p>
<p>
<strong>Foodie infighting aside, what place does tradition &ndash; be it of the Bible Belt or France &ndash; have when you&rsquo;re serving up artery-clogging fare?</strong>
</p>
</div><!-- /.articlecopy -->
